# Startup Types

Startup type determines when Windows starts a service.

---

## 1. Automatic

Service starts immediately during system boot.

Examples:

* DNS Client
* DHCP Client
* Event Log

PowerShell

```powershell
Get-Service Winmgmt
```

---

## 2. Automatic (Delayed Start)

Windows waits until boot is mostly complete before starting the service.

Benefits:

* Faster boot.
* Lower CPU usage during startup.
* Better boot performance.

Examples:

* Windows Search
* Background Intelligent Transfer Service (BITS)

---

## 3. Manual

Service starts only when:

* A user starts it.
* An application requests it.
* Another service triggers it.

Example:

Remote Registry

---

## 4. Disabled

Service cannot be started unless it is first re-enabled.

Used for:

* Security hardening.
* Unused features.
* Legacy services.

Example:

Fax service (if unused)

---

### Check Startup Type

```powershell
Get-CimInstance Win32_Service |
Select Name, StartMode
```

---

### Change Startup Type

Automatic

```powershell
Set-Service Spooler -StartupType Automatic
```

Manual

```powershell
Set-Service Spooler -StartupType Manual
```

Disabled

```powershell
Set-Service Spooler -StartupType Disabled
```

